<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>ENVIRONMENTAL AUDIT COMMITTEE INQURY ON MARINE PROTECTED AREAS</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Defra</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">INTRODUCTION</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has an ambitious programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to protect and enhance the marine environment while supporting sustainable use of its resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to achieve its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> vision of ‘clean, healthy, safe, productive and biologically diverse oceans and seas’.  Designation of marine protected areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(MPAs) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is one </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strand of this programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Others include management and regulation of economic activities which take place in the marine environment for example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">implementing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reforms we secured to the Common Fisheries Policy to manage fish stocks more sustainably and eliminate the waste of discarding dead fish, for the first time establishing marine plans around our coast to help achieve efficient management of competing uses of our seas while safeguarding the environment and implementing the improved system for marine licensing. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Another tool in achieving the Government’s vision is specific protection for important marine species for example, cetaceans, seahorses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> some fish species</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  All of these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">initiatives contribute to achieving good environmental status in our seas by 2020 as required under the EU Marine Strategy Framework Directive.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Marine Protected Areas</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To help deliver the marine vision, UK administrations have committed to contributing to an ecologically coherent network of MPAs in the North East Atlantic</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Achieving this commitment will also achieve international UK commitments.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Marine nature conservation policy is devolved and although each Administration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is following the OSPAR</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> principles for designing MPA networks, each has interpreted these differently and is taking a different approach to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">identifying</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">marine protected areas under national legislation.  For England, Wales &amp; Northern Ireland these are marine conservation zones (MCZs); for Scotland they are nature conservation Marine Protected Areas.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">paper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> covers the approach taken in the waters </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is responsible for – English inshore waters and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">offshore waters adjacent to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Engl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Northern Ir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eland (described as Secretary of State’s (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SoS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) waters in this paper)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(the Act) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">created a duty on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to establish a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> network of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MPAs which contributes to the conservation or improvement of the marine environment, is representative of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">range of features present in the UK marine area, and reflects that conservation of a feature may require designation of more than one site. The Act also provided for designation of national sites - marine conservation zones (MCZs) to complement existing types of MPAs to form the network and allowed for social and economic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consideration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s to be taken into account in selecting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MCZs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for designation.  Complementary Marine Acts have been made in Scotland</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Northern Ireland</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for their territorial waters out to 12 nautical miles (nm)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The existing types of MPAs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which contribute to the network </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">include Special Areas of Conservation (SAC) established under the Habitats Directive, Special Protection Areas (SPA) for birds established under the Wild Birds Directive and Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI)</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Numbers of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> different types of MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the waters for which the Secretary of State is responsible  are shown in the table below along with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">total </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">numbers for UK waters:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:3.3pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:92.1pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Type of MPA</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:148.85pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">SoS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> waters</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:163pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">UK waters</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:92.1pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SAC</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:148.85pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">44</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:163pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">108</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:92.1pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SPA</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:148.85pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">44</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:163pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">108</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:92.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">SSSI</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:148.85pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">113</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:163pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">297</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:92.1pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCZ</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:148.85pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">27</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:163pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Scotland has recently completed consultation on 33 possible nature conservation MPAs (equivalent to MCZs)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Northern Ireland has one MCZ established through its Marine Act</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Currently over 9% of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">marine area (inshore and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">offshores</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and 24.5% of English waters out to 12nm are contained within marine protected areas</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Marine Conservation Zones</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The first tranche of 27 MCZs was designated in November 2013.  These sites were selected from the 127 site recommendations made by four regional MCZ projects following</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consideration of the accompanying impact assessment, advice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from the independent Science Advisory Panel and formal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> advice from Natural England </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(NE) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and the Joint Nature Conservation Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (JNCC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Selection of the sites for consultation was made on the basis of the environmental benefits offered by the sites, the social and economic implications of designation and the adequacy of the supporting evidence base.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">formal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consultation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proposed 31 MCZ sites for designation and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ran from December 2012 until March 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ver 40,000 responses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> were received</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Following evaluation of the consultation responses and updated advice from NE and JNCC taking account of new evidence including that supplied in response to the consultation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Ministers decided to designate 27 sites.  One site at Hythe Bay is subject to further consideration with local stakeholder</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> before a decision on designation will be made.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> sites </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Hilbre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Island Group and Stour and Orwell) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will not be pursued further as a result of response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to the consultation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  A decision on a third site (North of Celtic Deep) has been deferred at the request of the Welsh Government. The Government response to the consultation is available on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pages of the GOV.UK website.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the same time as designating the first MCZs the Government also announced plans for designating two further tranches of MCZs over the next three years.  Consultation on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">first of these is expected in early 2015 with designation of sites by the end of 2015.  The third tranche is expected to follow a year later.  Detailed designation plans </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the second tranche are expected to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be published </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shortly. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These tranches of MCZs and completion of the work on SPAs (see paragraph 51 below) are expected to complete the English contribution to the ecologically coherent network meeting the requirements of the Act and achieving Government’s international commitments.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">IMPLEMENTATION OF THE FIRST TRANCHE OF MCZS</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Designation Orders for the 27 MCZs made on 21 November 2013 are legal instruments which came into force on 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> December 2013.  The making of these Orders conferred duties on public authorities to carry out their functions in such a way as to further, or if this is not possible, least hinder, the achievement of the conservation objectives of the sites.  Public authorities were advised of their new responsibilities regarding MCZs via the European Marine Site Officers Group which includes representatives from all the key regulators with a marine role.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Designation Orders define the location </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and area </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">each</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> MCZ, the features </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(habitats and species) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be protected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n the site and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their conservation objective or objectives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Accompanying material e.g. advice from NE/JNCC and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">factsheets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (see below)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> define the general management approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">required to achieve a features conservation objective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e. recover to favourable condition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maintain at favourable condition)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  The next section describes what the main marine regulators are doing to put in place measures to achieve the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conservation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">objectives.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Recognising the need for clear and accessible information on marine protected areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has produced factsheets</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for each of the designated sites which explain the location of the site, what features it is protecting and details of expected management.  The factsheets will be updated as new information becomes available.  These have been positively received by stakeholders.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">JNCC and NE provide more detailed scientific information on these sites, together with descriptions and images of the MPA features via their websites. The JNCC’s MPA Interactive Map shows all MPAs in the UK and allows the user to zoom into sites of interest and see additional supporting information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">MANAGEMENT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> ENFORCEMENT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AND MONITORING </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">OF EXISTING MCZS TAKING ACCOUNT OF STAKEHOLDER NEEDS</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Marine Management </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Organisation (MMO) is the Government’s principal marine regulator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for English waters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and plays a significant role in delivering the Government’s conservation aims for marine biodiversity. It does this when carrying out its full range of functions such as those connected with marine planning and marine licensing, for example by taking account of the general duties on public authorities to conserve biodiversity and to protect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SACs and SPAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as well as the new duties under the Act to contribute to the achievement of sustainable development and further MCZ conservation objectives. In addition to its general duties (which apply to all public authorities) the MMO has specific statutory functions for nature conservation that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> include powers of inspection and enforcement, making byelaws and issuing licen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The MMO has provided guidance on how it will exercise its licensing functions</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and byelaw-making</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> powers in relation to MCZs.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> modernised inshore fisheries management arrangements in England by replacing Sea Fisheries Committees (SFCs) with Inshore Fisheries and Conservation Authorities (IFCAs), whose purpose is to manage sustainably the exploitation of sea fisheries resources in their districts. IFCAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have fisheries and conservation responsibilities in the 0-6nm zone and a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">duty to protect the marine environment from the impact of fishing on marine ecosystems. IFCAs have powers of inspection and enforcement as well as strengthened byelaw-making powers (for inshore fisheries activities) to ensure more effective management of marine habitats in the inshore area. This includes activities such as bait digging and seaweed gathering which were not regulated by SFCs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As well as the MMO and IFCAs a number of other public authorities have duties to protect MPAs with regard to activities which they regulate.  These include the Environment Agency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (coastal and estuarine management) and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Department for Energy and Climate Change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (oil and gas licensing)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">MCZ Site Management and stakeholder involvement</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uties on Public Authorities apply from the point at which a Designation Order is made and all relevant public authorities have been alerted to the designation of MCZs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Government took a policy decision that MCZ sites are considered within licence applications from the point they are included in a public consultation where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> indicates it is minded to designate them.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MMO and IFCAs are currently considering what management </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approaches</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are required on each site to achieve the conservation objectives.  Normal practice for other types of MPA is for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">statutory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nature conservation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bodies (NE and JNCC) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to provide detailed conservation advice to regulators who then consider, with stakeholders as appropriate, what management </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">actions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are needed to achieve conservation objectives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, including whether specific management measures are required under legislation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uch of this information is already available through the regional MCZ project process and the formal advice from SNCBs.  Government has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">asked</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> regulators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> use of this information now and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NE and JNCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and stakeholders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ahead of receiving formal conservation advice to put </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a timetable for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">management measures on designated MCZs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in place as soon as possible.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In order to facilitate the process of establishing management and ensure that the features and sites at highest risk are addressed first, NE and MMO have developed a risk prioritisation matrix.  This has been provided to IFCAs to provide a local perspective on risks to help identify the highest priorities.  This work is currently underway and will be made publicly available shortly.  MMO and IFCAs will be integrating their work plans for putting in place management regimes on MCZs with ongoing work to manage activities on SACs and SPAs.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where other Member States fish in MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in waters beyond </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the 6 nm limits, particular procedures need to be followed under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Common Fisheries Policy (CFP).  These include holding discussions with relevant EU Member States which have historic fishing rights in the 6 – 12nm zone and/or fishing interests in the 12-200nm zone to develop management proposals for the MPAs.  There are also requirements to discuss management proposals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regionally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with stakeholders including through the relevant Advisory Council.   The CFP sets out the process for agreeing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">necessary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">management measures including involvement of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">European Commission, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">European Parliament and Fisheries Council.  The lead regulator for MPAs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> - 12</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> zone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is the MMO.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the 12-200nm zone, the European Commission is responsible for bringing measures into force (through a Commission Regulation) at the request of Member States. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With JNCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, MMO has developed a plan for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">implementing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">management measures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for SACs and SPAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> based on grouping sites geographically.  MCZs in these areas will be included as part of discussions with other Member States and stakeholders.  Current plans for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">offshore sites</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are to submit any necessary management </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">measures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to European processes by the end of 2014/15 with the aim of having the management measures in place as soon as possible thereafter.  This will depend on the timetable of the European processes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Regulators are expected to follow their usual practices in developing management approaches for MCZs.  Normally these involve extensive engagement with stakeholders and in some cases, e.g. byelaws, formal consultation.  Regulators are expected to follow the Hampton principles</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on reducing administrative burdens on public authorities and consider voluntary approaches before regulatory measures.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the Ministerial statement of 21 November 2013, Government set an expectation of stakeholders working in partnership to enable the management of sites.  This is vital if management actions are to have local support leading to successfully managed sites. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Enforcement</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Marine Act provided both MMO and IFCAs with enforcement powers regarding regulating activities to protect MPAs and enable them to achieve conservation objectives. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where MMO has powers to enforce MPA management measures, for example for MMO byelaws within 0-12nm or for EC regulations from 12-200nm, an intelligence led, risk based approach to enforcement is undertaken.  Where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">intelligence suggests non-compliance or a risk of non-compliance with a management measure, the area will be subject to enhanced scrutiny using available surface and remote surveillance assets.  This may include Navy fisheries protection vessel presence, aerial surveillance or joint operations with other UK agencies (for example the IFCAs and Environment Agency within 12nm) or other Member State regulating bodies (in areas where those other Member State’s fishing vessels have access rights).  MMO would coordinate any joint operations and the frequency and intensity of enforcement will be determined by risk and intelligence.  Monitoring measures may also be employed requiring vessels to report their position at frequent regular intervals.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The princip</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s by which the MMO will regulate MPAs are set out by the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006 and the Regulators' Compliance Code</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and aim to ensure that the MMO is proportionate, accountable, consistent, transparent and targeted in any enforcement action it takes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">IFCAs also take a risk-based approach to enforcement in the 0 – 6 nm area. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has provided guidance to the IFCAs on establishing a common enforcement framework.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Governance</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NE, JNCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and regulators are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">currently reviewing possible frameworks to facilitate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improved processes for co-ordinating and reporting on actions required, and being implemented to achieve conservation objectives for MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Plans are in the early stages of development with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an aim to introduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new arrangements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">later in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2014.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Monitoring</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NE and JNCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have responsibility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for monitoring and reporting on the condition (ecological quality or state) of all marine protected areas.  Within 12nm of the coast Natural England is responsible for sites in English waters.  JNCC is responsible for monitoring sites in UK offshore waters.  The results of the monitoring will indicate the status of the species or habitats at the site in relation to their conservation objectives. It informs advice on whether management action is achieving desired results or whether additional management action may be needed. Monitoring of SACs, SPAs and SSSIs has been operating for more than a decade, and it is anticipated that monitoring for new MCZs will employ a similar </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strategy and methods. The marine monitoring programme has increased significantly over the last five years, benefiting from additional funding from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.    </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">EVIDENCE BASE FOR MCZs</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government considers that it is vital  that there is an adequate evidence base for each individual site to ensure that we have successful well managed MCZs.   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To date </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has spent approximately £8m gathering seabed and habitat mapping evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to support decisions on the designation and future management of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MCZs and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">committed to spending a further £2m this financial year.  This funding has supported the gathering of seabed and habitat data for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over 60 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prospective sites.  While much of the evidence has been gathered by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cefas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and other Government bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a proportion of the work has been subject to competitive tender bringing in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> commercial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations from outside government to gather information to pre-agreed standards.  This has enabled the MCZ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> survey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> information collected to be publicly available through the Marine Environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and Information network (MEDIN).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The seabed and habitat data collection programmes for MCZs have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> significantly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> increased the proportion of English/UK seabed that has been mapped in detail.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government expects to continue to gather evidence to support MCZ designation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with an anticipated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">spend </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2014-15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  We will also continue to explore opportunities to improve the information we have on our marine environment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As well as improving the evidence base on seabed habitats</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Government has also carried out work to improve the evidence base on social and economic factors.  As part of the process for designating the first tranche of MCZs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> data on the range of economic activities on each site w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> collected to enable the impacts of designation to be calculated.   Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ese data were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> further refined through the consultation where a number of responses provided clarification around estimated costs.  This work will be repeated for sites being considered for designation in future tranches so that good decisions, balancing environmental, social and economic, can be made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a significant gap in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence base regarding benefits of designation.  While it is possible to describe the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> broad ecosystem benefits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> qualitatively, little evidence exists to enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more detailed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">quantification.  Government is funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> projects on valuing improvements in ecosystem services in the marine environment and is continually collating existing studies as they become available to improve the social and economic evidence base.  This is an ongoing process and Government will review the need to fund further projects to fill gaps in knowledge and aid decision-making. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As well as gathering evidence to support MCZ designation, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and partner organisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have collected evidence related to other types of MPA.  This has included surveying some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SACs and SPAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decisions on appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">management of these sites and meet the requirements of the Habitats and Wild Birds Directives.  Looking more strategically </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has also funded work on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">utonomous vehicles exploring possibilities of using th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for MPA and habitat surveys.  If successful this work could result in significant cost savings as the need for expensive survey ship time is reduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Natural Environment Research Council (NERC) is one of the biggest funders of marine science in the UK and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is actively engaged with NERC to ensure there is s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ubstantial co-operation and alignment of marine related programmes and resources. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has assigned approximately £5 million over 10 years in support of joint programming, with NERC contributing between £18 - £20m. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Two new NERC/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> j</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ointly funded programmes will help inform the delivery of MCZs and MPAs. The UK Shelf Seas Biogeochemistry programme, which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> started in October 2013. This has dedicated research to look at the effects of disturbance such as trawling as well as carbon cycling and storage in relation to MCZs and MPAs. The second is a new co-funded Marine Ecosystems Programme where work on MCZs’ areas will be used to model and assess food web relationships and will contribute to the work on developing cohesive MCZ networks.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is fully engaged in NERC’s programme considering the benefits and potential risks of giving independent status to three of its wholly-owned centres, the British Geological Survey (BGS), National Oceanography Centre (NOC) and Centre for Ecology &amp; Hydrology (CEH), and of giving the National Centre for Atmospheric Science (NCAS) a similar independent identity. Following NERC Council’s decision in December 2013 to proceed to the next stage of more detailed analysis of options to inform a second gateway decision in July 2014, NERC have established a ‘Whitehall Reference Group’ to enable structured input from central government to the programme. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, along with other key departments, will be represented on this Group. In addition, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Chief Scientific Adviser (Professor Ian Boyd) sits on NERC Council.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">BALANCING SOCIAL, ECONOMIC AND ENVIRONMENTAL FACTORS IN CONSIDERING FUTURE MCZS</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Selecting the first tranche of MCZs for consultation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The MCZs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consulted on and designated in the first tranche were selected from the recommendations made by the four regional MCZ projects considering environmental benefits, social and economic implications and the adequacy of the evidence base. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> aim was to find the right balance between the strength of the conservation advantages an MCZ offered, relative to the economic and social implications of its likely designation. Where a site's </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conservation advantages were considered to outweigh the economic and social costs then the MCZ was considered appropriate for possible designation at some point. Whether an MCZ, and all of its features, was ready for designation in the 2013 tranche depended on the levels of confidence in the scientific evidence. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Weighing up conservation benefits against socio-economic costs was a difficult exercise because some of the economic impacts are expressed in monetary terms while the social and ecological benefits were often expressed in qualitative terms with no monetary value assigned to them.  In addition, the socio-economic benefits from designation (e.g. growth in tourism) are difficult to predict and attribute to MCZs due to the many factors that contribute to growth in a particular sector.  Further complexity stemmed from the wide range of ecological targets to which each site contributed differently; these were assessed in detail in the SNCB advice provided in July 2012. The approach to determining which recommended MCZs were proposed for designation in the first tranche is summarised below.  More detail about the process is available on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pages of the GOV.UK website</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The most expensive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MCZs</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> needed to provide a greater ecological contribution to outweigh their high socio-economic costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  These were only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">considered suitable for inclusion in the network if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d a feature or features </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for which there are limited opportunities to protect it nationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and/or the best regional examples of a feature or features</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A number of recommended sites had either high </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unquantified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> costs or quantified cost predictions which spanned a very wide range (for example costs associated with renewable energy generation, non-UK fisheries and aquaculture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  These were not included in the potential first tranche sites but will be subject to further assessment and clarification of costs as part of being considered for designation in the second or third tranches. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The third element of considering whether a site was suitable for inclusion in the first tranche was the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ecological </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence base supporting it. Given that the current state of knowledge of seabed characteristics is limited in some areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government considered that an adequate evidence base was necessary to support decisions that may have socio-economic impacts and effects on people’s livelihoods and result in enforcement and monitoring costs that fall on the tax payer.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is also important to enable successful management of sites particularly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where management measures have to be agreed with other EU Member States through the CFP procedures (see paragraph 21). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For the designation of first tranche MCZs adequate evidence was high or moderate confidence in presence and extent of features based on the advice provided by NE and the JNCC except in specific circumstances for features at higher risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of damage or loss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, where a lower certainty of data was accepted in accordance with the Precautionary Principle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.   We tried to strike an appropriate balance between being sufficiently sure of a feature's presence, extent and condition, whilst not setting data requirements that are unreasonable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">given current (and likely future) data availability on seabed characteristics. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Following the consultation NE and JNCC updated their advice taking into account additional evidence gathered through the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-funded work and evidence supplied during the consultation. Social and economic costs were also updated along with inclusion of additional information on benefits which was not available pre-consultation.  Consideration of the updated evidence and consultation responses led to 27 sites being designated in November 2013.  One site at Hythe Bay, is being further considered </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local stakeholders with the intention making a decision on designation by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">end </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">March 2014.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Planned approach for second tranche</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ministers have indicated that decisions on sites for designation in the second and third tranches will follow the same principles as for the first i.e. balancing environmental benefits with social and economic implications and consideration of the adequacy of the evidence base.  Decisions will again be reliant on the adequacy of the evidence base.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A key component of the consideration of the environmental advantages of a site will be its contribution to completing the English element of the ECN as well as its innate environmental advantages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. NE and JNCC will be providing advice on this.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At this stage we have not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">finalised the detailed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the process for making decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the designation of second and third tranche sites</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will be refined over the next few months and details published when finalised.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">FUTURE PLANS</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government, with the Devolved Administrations has committed to contributing to an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ECN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the North East Atlantic.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the Written Ministerial Statement to Parliament on 21 November 2013, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Government announced its commitment to two further tranches of MCZs to complete the English contribution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to the network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The first of these is expected to be consulted on in early 2015 with sites designated by the end of that year.  The final tranche of MCZs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is expected to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">follow a year later.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of the components of the network good progress has been made on establishing S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with marine components </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">under the Habitats Directive which protect habitats and species of European importance with the UK contribution considered to be complete with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">08 sites of which 44 are in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SoS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> waters.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For seabirds there are currently 108 SPAs with marine components established under the EU Wild Birds Directive. 44 of these are in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SoS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> waters.  The Government’s plans are to identify the remaining marine SPAs needed to complete the SPA network by the end of 2015. Once complete they will provide protection for all regularly occurring and migratory seabird species found in the UK (with the exception of Black Guillemot which is not covered by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> SPA requirements of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Directive).  Consultations on two further SPAs for the protection of seabirds at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Flamborough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Head and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Filey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> coast and at Falmouth Bay to St Austell Bay commenced on 20 January 2014</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Consultations on a further potential fourteen sites are expected in late 2014/early 2015.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the UK there are currently around 300 SSSIs or equivalents with marine components which contribute to the network</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. 113 of these are in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SoS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> waters</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  NE is currently reviewing its SSSI series and will conduct a review of SSSIs in English inshore waters by March 2016.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We believe it is important that sites are managed to achieve the anticipated benefits rather than simply being lines on maps.  The Government has therefore committed to 25% of English waters being within a well-managed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by 2016</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and with the DAs, committed to the OSPAR target </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to contribute to a well- managed ecologically coherent network in the North East Atlantic by 2016.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  With the recent MCZs designations 24.5% of English waters is within MPAs, assuming that the two SPAs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">currently being consulted on are designated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increase.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As noted above work is underway to implement management </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">actions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and new MPAs and we are currently on track to meet national and international targets. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While we cannot at this stage say how many more MPAs are likely to be designated we believe that these will make a substantial English contribution to the network meeting national and international commitments on MPAs.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">31 January 2014</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">UK Contribution to Ecologically Coherent MPA Network in the North East Atlantic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Joint Administrations Statement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">: </span><a href="http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/0041/00411304.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/0041/00411304.pdf</span></a></p><h1 style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">Ospar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal"> Guidance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">n Developing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">n Ecologically Coherent Network </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">Ospar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal"> Marine Protected Areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">(Reference number 2006-3)</span></h1><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2010/5/pdfs/asp_20100005_en.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2010/5/pdfs/asp_20100005_en.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.doeni.gov.uk/marine_act__northern_ireland__2013.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.doeni.gov.uk/marine_act__northern_ireland__2013.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The Act also includes sites designated under the RAMSAR wetlands convention.  In England most of these are designated as SSSIs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> SSSIs figures may be subject to change as ongoing work between JNCC and the SNCBs will standardise how SSSIs and their features are classed as marine.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">  </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/report-to-parliament-on-the-marine-protected-areas-network"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/report-to-parliament-on-the-marine-protected-areas-network</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> SSSI or equivalent.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> These figures exclude the area covered by SSSIs and equivalents.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/marine-conservation-zones-consultation-on-proposals-for-designation-in-2013"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/marine-conservation-zones-consultation-on-proposals-for-designation-in-2013</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Inshore sites </span><a href="http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/category/1721481"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/category/1721481</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. Offshore sites </span><a href="http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-6561"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-6561</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/protecting/conservation/mcz.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/protecting/conservation/mcz.htm</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/licensing/supporting/mcz.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/licensing/supporting/mcz.htm</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.bis.gov.uk/files/file22988.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bis.gov.uk/files/file22988.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family: